post_text: Our team took part in a video for the Oklahoma State Department of Education prior to COVID-19. The video was just released to encourage the community to complete the census.
shared_text:
Oklahoma State Department of Education
September 14 at 2:48 PM ·

Did you know that federal funding is critical to public education? Federal funds, which are determined by Census numbers, provide nearly $1 billion for child nutrition programs, special education services, afterschool programs and more.

Learn how to bring the Census alive for your students by watching the video below! And access a variety of Census-related lesson plans and resources here: https://www.census.gov/schools

Help secure funding for Oklahoma schools by completing the Census at 2020census.gov. It's quick and easy!

shared_text:
Mid-Del Schools (Oklahoma) added 25 new photos.
September 11 at 9:26 PM ·

Prior to tonight's game, members of Robert Kalsu's family were on hand for the rededication of Robert Kalsu Stadium. In addition, former teammates from Del City High School, the University of Oklahoma, and the Buffalo Bills were present for the celebration. The colors were presented by the University of Oklahoma ARMY ROTC Cadets.

A presentation on behalf of the City of Del City was made by Senator Brenda Stanley, Representative Andy Fugate, and Mayor Floyd Eason. Head Coach Mike Dunn presented a football signed by the players to Bob Kalsu, Jr. Principal Gina Hill presented the Kalsu family with a framed picture of the new stadium.

Thank you to our community who provided these improvements to Robert Kalsu Stadium with the passage of the 2017 bond election. #mdpurpose

Mid-Del Virtual Academy Parents: If your student is not seeing any classes when they login to Edgenuity, we are aware of this issue. It is on Edgenuity's end and we are working quickly to resolve the issue. Please have your student check in Edgenuity periodically throughout the day to see if courses are activated. Your student will not be penalized in any way for not being able to login to courses.

If you are having other login issues, i.e. student email, or cannot log in to Edgenuity, there is a document on your school's website to help resolve those issues. https://core-docs.s3.amazonaws.com/documents/asset/uploaded_file/877167/Edgenuity_Steps_To_Logging_In.pdf

If after completing these steps, and you have not been successful in gaining access to your Edgenuity account, please email edgenuityquestions@mid-del.net with the following information:
Student First and Last Name
Grade Level
Parent First and Last Name

Thank you for your continued patience during this time.

post_text: Our top priority is to maintain the health and safety of our students and staff, and according to health officials, proper face coverings may help significantly reduce the transmission of COVID-19, even when a person is not feeling ill. The district will require students and staff to wear a face covering during the school day. Evidence shows a decrease in COVID-19 when a face covering is worn. All students and staff will be provided a neck gaiter at the start of school. We've attached a document that outlines acceptable face covering options for Mid-Del Schools. Thank you.

post_text:
Please help us congratulate Ms. Suzanna Bennett, the new Assistant Principal at Tinker Elementary!

She has been an educator for 9 years, spending all but one year in Mid-Del Public Schools. Bennett taught 4th grade for five years and spent the last four years as a 5th grade teacher. She has been involved in elementary sports and other academic clubs in the district. Suzanna earned her Bachelor’s of Science in Education with a focus on Elementary Education from Oklahoma Christian University. She then earned her Master’s in Education with a focus on Educational Leadership at the University of Central Oklahoma.

The Mid-Del Central Office will be closed today, Wednesday, July 8, 2020. This morning, we received notice of an employee who has tested positive for COVID-19. Out of an abundance of caution, we sent all employees home for the day in order to sanitize all touch surfaces in the building. The Central Office will be open for business as usual on Thursday, July 9. This does not affect ongoing work at any other Mid-Del location.

The Mid-Del Central Office is located at 7217 S.E. 15th Street in Midwest City.

Feed the Children- Teacher Store
July 6 at 10:24 AM ·

OK area!

Opening this year will look different... we have new guidelines in place, for your safety and ours. Here are a few of the changes..

Opening will begin July 28th this year. For July 28-30, and Aug 3-6, we will be open 8-5. If you shop the end of July, that will count as your August visit!
You will be required to sign up to shop. We will post a link to sign up in the coming week. This includes opening, and throughout the entire school year.

ONLY 50 teachers in a one hour time slot will be able to shop. Each time slot will begin on the hour.
We ask that you do not bring children, spouses, friends, ect, as there are only 50 slots available.

Masks will be required. We will disinfect shopping carts before the new hour starts for the next group of teachers. Please practice social distancing of 6 feet.

We will have more information coming, so stay tuned!

post_text: Great job Mr. Kelly Fry for your time on this project!
shared_text:
Del Crest Middle School is with Del Crest Junior High.
July 3 at 7:39 PM ·

As we approached the 2019-2020 school year, I had a thought to do a memory video that captures what makes this school so unique. When the pandemic hit and schools closed early, many of the final events that were planned to close out the school had to be cancelled. Because of that, I really struggled with how to approach this video. I have every yearbook except for 3 or 4. So, I decided to take a look back starting in 1962 and work my way forward. Hopefully, you will see your friends, or yourself, and it will spark memories and conversations about the times shared inside the walls of Del Crest Junior High/Middle School.

This is a glimpse, a snapshot if you will, of time gone by. Part 1 focuses on the 60s and 70s. Part 2 will cover the 80s and 90s while part 3 will be from 2000 to 2020 and the end of the school as we know it.

I hope you enjoy Del Crest Heights: A Look Back

post_text: The Mid-Del Bond election passed with a 62.9% approval. On behalf of the Mid-Del Board of Education and everyone who worked hard to get this bond proposal put together, I want to thank our community for continuing to support our 14,000+ students. Today’s YES vote will help us meet instructional needs, support our fine arts programs, improve our playgrounds, and make our campuses more accessible for all students. It’s great to work and live in a community that believes in public education! Dr. Rick Cobb, Superintendent of Mid-Del Schools

post_text: We have heard from members of the community that a few polling locations had not given out the ballot to vote in the Mid-Del Bond Election. The election board has been notified. Our Mid-Del Enrollment Center will open on July 6th at the Mid-Del Learning and Services Center located at 4731 Judy Drive in Del City.

We have a new process for enrollment in Mid-Del. Parents must register for an appointment time for the CEC. This includes new student enrollment as well as students on a resident affidavit. Families who "walk-up" to the Enrollment Center will have to register for an appointment at a later time.

Save time when visiting the Mid-Del Enrollment Center by adding yourself to the QLess Virtual Line. Instead of spending valuable time waiting in line, you can add yourself to the virtual line and you will be notified when you are next in line for service.

Families can begin scheduling appointments on Monday, June 29. All patrons and families must wear a mask when coming to the CEC. Masks will not be provided. For questions, please email enrollment@mid-del.net. Thank you!

UPDATE:
*6/23/20: Families can now schedule your enrollment appointments by using this link: https://kiosk.na4.qless.com/kiosk/app/home/241

On Friday, we shared a letter on social media to our Mid-Del Community surrounding the death of George Floyd. In that letter, we said, "We stamp the words, 'Mid-Del Schools: Safe, Challenged, and Ready' on just about every document and social media post that we release. That’s who we aspire to be. To get closer to that goal, we all have to get better about reflecting on our own biases and working to eliminate them. We have to stand up and say something when we see someone in a position of authority misusing that power."

Over the weekend, an educator in our district made comments from his personal social media account that were the exact opposite of this vision and the values of our community. We do not condone the employee's words or behavior. While we cannot comment on employee personnel issues, we want our students, families and our community to know that we will not tolerate this conduct. We expect all of our staff to embrace the diversity of our district and support the families we serve.

Dr. Rick Cobb,
Superintendent of Schools

On January 28, 2020, the Mid-Del Board of Education approved a resolution to hold a bond election Tuesday, April 7, 2020. Due to the COVID-19 Pandemic, the Board of Education moved the election date to June 30, 2020.

The total bond amount is $8,840,000. Each school would receive improvements on this bond. The projects in the bond election include playground equipment, improved accessibility, band/orchestra uniforms, fine arts equipment, bathroom and classroom renovations, and security upgrades.

If the bond passes, millage rates will remain the same. This is NOT a property tax increase for our community.

The deadline to register to vote in this election is Friday, June 5, 2020. If you'd like to receive an absentee ballot, those must be requested no later than June 23, 2020. You may request an absentee ballot online from the state election board: https://www.ok.gov/elections/OVP.html.

For more information, please email sboyer@mid-del.net.

#mdpurpose

post_text:
Mr. Nathan Elliott was named the 2020-2021 Head Principal for Midwest City High School during the May 19, 2020, Board of Education meeting. Mr. Elliott has been an administrator at Kerr Middle School for the past five years, the last three years as head principal. He was recently named as the head principal for Del City Middle School. Prior to working in Mid-Del, Mr. Elliott was a teacher and a coach in Ada Public Schools for 15 years and taught one year in Newcastle.

Mr. Elliott earned his Masters in Education Administration and his Bachelors in Secondary Education from East Central University. He will be filling the vacancy created by Dr. LaShonda Broiles who is transitioning to Executive Director for Secondary Instruction for the Mid-Del District.

Please help us congratulate Mr. Elliott! #mdpurpose #oklaed

We will have an opportunity for our families to drive-up to our photo booths that will be located in front of the field house at each of our three high schools on May 21st from 12:00 p.m.-6:00 p.m. and May 22nd from 8:00 a.m.-12:00 p.m. to take pictures of seniors in their cap and gowns. post_text:
We'd like to welcome Ms. Heather Dunn as the new Principal of Townsend Elementary for the 2020-2021 School Year.

Ms. Heather Dunn has been in education for 13 years, with the majority of them in Mid-Del serving as a classroom teacher and instructional coach. She currently serves as an assistant principal for Santa Fe South Schools in Oklahoma City. Ms. Dunn received her Bachelor’s degree in Early Childhood Education and Master’s degrees in Instructional Leadership and Academic Curriculum as well as Educational Leadership.

Dunn will be filling the vacancy created by Mr. Rod Boyer's retirement. Please help us welcome back Ms. Dunn! #mdpurpose

post_text:
Please help us congratulate Dr. LaShonda Broiles, the new Executive Director for Secondary Instruction for Mid-Del Schools for the 2020-2021 School Year.

Dr. LaShonda Broiles has been in education for over 20 years, spending the most recent 13 years of her career in Mid-Del. She has served the district as head principal at Jarman Middle School and Midwest City High School.
Dr. Broiles graduated from Langston University with a Bachelor’s of Science in Special Education. She received a Master’s of Education in School Administration from the University of Central Oklahoma and a Doctorate of Education from Walden University.

Broiles will be filling the vacancy created by Dr. Cordell Ehrich's transition to Assistant Superintendent for Teaching and Learning for the 2020-2021 School Year.

Please help us congratulate Dr. Broiles!

post_text: Great job Aaron!
shared_text:
Midwest City High School Home of the Bombers
May 1 at 3:28 PM ·

Aaron Foreman, a 2016 Bomber graduate and National Merit Scholar, is graduating from OU in May. He has maintained a perfect 4.0 throughout his entire college career and has majored in Computer Engineering. He is also in the accelerated Master’s program. He is finishing up his first year of his Master’s and will graduate with that next year. We all know it takes a village to raise a child and Midwest City High School is happy to have been just one small part of Aaron’s success so far. We are Bomber proud and can’t wait to see the amazing things he will do. Remember... Once a Bomber, Always a Bomber!
#OnceaBomberAlwaysaBomber #MCHSDECASportsMarketingTeam

Carl Albert High School
April 21 at 10:43 AM ·

Congratulations to the Carl Albert High School Titans! They have been recognized by U.S. News as a 2020 Best High School. The organization numerically ranked nearly 18,000 schools nationwide this year.

The 2020 edition of Best High Schools includes a numerical ranking of nearly all public high schools in each state and each census-designated metropolitan area with three or more high schools, as well as the Best STEM Schools ranking and comprehensive Best Charter Schools and Best Magnet Schools rankings. There are also rankings of high schools for school districts with three or more high schools.

With today’s launch, U.S. News has published detailed school-specific information on enrollment, graduation rates, student body demographics, location, school type and results of state assessments, as well as Advanced Placement and International Baccalaureate tests.

Congratulations Titans!

Mid-Del is happy to welcome our new Executive Director of Technology and Data, Dr. Scott Haselwood. He has hit the ground running after joining the team and is helping meet the needs of our District and Mid-Del families.

Dr. Scott Haselwood was the Senior Educational Technologist at Oklahoma City University. He has worked as a professor in higher education and as classroom teacher, primarily high school mathematics. Scott earned his Bachelors degree from the University of Central Oklahoma, his Masters from Graceland University, his Doctorate in Education with an option in Educational Technology from Oklahoma State University, and received his National Board Certification in 2011.

Help us welcome Dr. Haselwood!

post_text:
We love GOOD NEWS stories! We want to recognize Emily Scrimshire from Del City High School! She raised money and has been making/donating masks for first responders, elderly and medical facilities.

Emily Scrimshire is a sophomore at Del City High School. She has a 3.8 GPA and was the All District Defensive Player of the Year for softball. Emily has made just under 100 masks and has orders for 100 more. All masks are completely free to first responders, elderly citizens and medical facilities. She has donated masks to the Oklahoma County Sheriff's Office, Canadian County Sheriff's Office, OK Army National Guard, several hospice and medical facilities, and countless others that do not have the means to purchase masks. She credits her teacher from home economics, Mrs. Davis, for teaching her this valuable skill.

Way to go Emily! #mdpurpose

post_text:
Congratulations to Mrs. Christy Combs, one of our amazing teachers at Country Estates Elementary, for being this week's Magic 104.1 Teacher Feature winner!

“This woman is constantly going above and beyond as an educator. She was my sons 1st grade AND 3rd grade teacher. Our family was going through a hard time and she didn’t even bat an eye to go the extra mile for my son to make sure that he was okay. During the teacher walk out she constantly made everything about HER STUDENTS l, and now with school out due to COVID-19 she is making videos of herself reading to her students and posting them online so that she can still be with them. She even went as far to dress up as the cat in the hat today. She’s truly a gem and we are so blessed and thankful to have her in our children’s lives. Yes, even though my kids don’t even go to that school anymore. She still calls to say hello and check up on them. We love her and she definitely deserves to be recognized for her AMAZING way of teaching and loving her students.” – Danika Stewart
http://magic104.com/teacher/

post_text: Dr. Silvya Kirk has been appointed to the Mid-Del Board of Education for Ward 2. She served the patrons of Mid-Del Schools from 1988-2016 as teacher, curriculum coordinator, principal, and secondary director. She has continued to stay active in the community after her retirement by serving groups such as the Mid-Del Public Schools Foundation and the Midwest City Kiwanis Club to name a few. Dr. Kirk replaces the seat vacated by Mr. Tim Blanton who resigned last month. Please help us welcome Dr. Silvya Kirk to the Mid-Del Board of Education. #mdpurpose #oklaed

Good morning! We are excited to offer learning enrichment opportunities for our students through our Continuous Learning Plan (CLP). We know our staff is looking forward to speaking with their students if they haven't already!

Our CLP can be found on the District website at the link below. CLP Paper packets may be picked up today between 9:30-11:00 a.m. at our eight feeding locations: Barnes Elementary, Highland Park Elementary, Midwest City Elementary, Soldier Creek Elementary, Steed Elementary, Tinker Elementary, Del City High School and Midwest City High School.

Our teachers will begin contacting you today to assist in this process. Please make sure your contact information is correct. If you need to update your contact information, please email your child's name(s), school, phone number and email. Be sure to include your name.

Thank you for being patient in this time of transition. Please direct questions to covidquestions@mid-del.net. We look forward to this new chapter of learning together! #mdpurpose #oklaed

Blessing comes in many forms, but for our SWAG recipient Savina and her mom Sabra, the blessings came directly from Troy McCollum. As many of you remember, Troy’s wife, Troyan, was our SWAG recipient in 2019. She lost her long battle with ALS in November, but they were so appreciative of everything our fund raising was able to provide for them in Troyan’s last months.

Carl Albert High School
April 1 at 8:36 PM ·

Titan Families,

Because we have a difficult route to cover, it would be difficult for our teachers to parade through the neighborhoods to wave at our students.

However, we desperately miss your sweet faces and want to see you. Therefore we will be having a drive-thru parade. Our teachers will be parked in the CAHS parking lot in front of the main building for you drive through to wave at the CAHS staff!

In order to comply with social distancing regulations, it will be drive through only and Titans will not be permitted to be out of their vehicles. We are also requesting that our student drivers comply with all social distancing guidelines before, during and after the event. We know you miss each other, but we need you all to stay healthy and safe!

This is a difficult time for all of us, but we wanted to make a way to see our students! Bring your signs, smiles, waves, and air hugs on Tuesday, April 7 between 6-7 PM!

WE CAN’T WAIT TO SEE YOU, TITANS! WE LOVE AND MISS YOU!

post_text: Barnes families. 💙
shared_text:
Barnes Elementary School
March 27 at 12:01 PM ·

Barnes Families,

Because we have a difficult route to cover, it would be difficult for our teachers to parade through the neighborhoods to wave at our kiddos.

However, we desperately miss your sweet faces and want to see you. Therefore we will be having a drive-thru parade. Our teachers will be parked in the Barnes parking lot for you to bring the kids and drive through to wave at the Barnes staff!

In order to comply with social distancing regulations, it will be drive through only and Bluejays will not be permitted to be out of their vehicles.

This is a difficult time for all of us, but we wanted to make a way to see our kiddos! Bring your signs, smiles, waves, and air hugs on Wednesday, April 1 between 5:30-6:30!

WE CAN’T WAIT TO SEE YOU, BLUEJAYS! WE LOVE AND MISS YOU!

shared_text:
Mid-Del Technology Center
March 23 at 10:39 PM ·

Mid-Del Tech proudly partners with local industries year-round to fulfill our mission of providing relevant technical education to students and qualified workers to our community. We rely on industry partners for internships, classroom presentations, field trips, mock interviews, job fairs, and so much more. Today MDTC had the opportunity to return the favor and donate face masks, gloves, isolation gowns, and sanitizing supplies to our local frontline medical heroes! Together we will carry on the Oklahoma Standard and weather this storm. #okcareertech #mdpurpose

Please note that while gathering, handling, and delivering these supplies all CDC and State Dept of Education Guidelines were followed.

post_text: Parents, As previously mentioned, all schools have been mandated to be closed until April 6th. Understanding that this was an unexpected occurrence, many families may need to pick up prescriptions for this period of time. Administrators will have schools open on Monday, March 23rd, from 9:00 a.m. until 12:00 p.m. for parents to pick up medication. Only individuals on the child’s pick up list may retrieve medication. Families will not have access to other areas of the schools for the duration of the closure. If this pick up time does not work for you, please contact your child’s school during this time period to make other arrangements with the building principal.

post_text:
Mid-Del Families,

As I’m sure you are all aware, there have been a lot of questions, concerns, and miscommunication in our community, which has led to an excessive amount of absences at many of our school sites. Although the recommendation from state health professionals is to keep schools open, we cannot ignore the large amount of absences anticipated for Friday. As a result, Mid-Del Public Schools will be closed on Friday, March 13th.

This closure will not require us to extend the school year since we have one more banked day available to us.

Over the break, all Mid-Del facilities will be closed for all activities, events, practices as well as rehearsals. During this time, we will continue to monitor developments related to COVID-19.

Stay safe and enjoy your Spring Break!

post_text: On January 28, 2020, our Board of Education approved a resolution to hold a bond election Tuesday, April 7, 2020. If the bond passes, millage rates will remain the same. This is NOT a property tax increase. The total bond amount is $8,840,000. Each school would receive improvements on this bond. #mdpurpose

shared_text:
Mid-Del Public Schools Foundation
March 3 at 2:43 PM ·

What. A. Night. The only thing better than putting on a successful event is waking up to find that we have been awarded a grant from the Midwest City Hospital Authority! This grant will provide shade structures along with tables and benches at all three of our middle schools for the next school year. With this grant the Foundation has officially raised and put over 1 million dollars back into Mid-Del Schools (Oklahoma)! We couldn’t do without our amazing community partners. Thank you to everyone who donates and supports the Foundation. Now, let’s get to work on the next million! #mdpurpose #mdfoundation

post_text:
Fifth Grade students at Townsend Elementary have been working diligently on a service project during their recess and at home. Using donated yarn and knitting looms, they are making nests, joey pouches, and blankets for the many animals injured in the Australian wildfires. They are also making hats for Infant Crisis Services, children with cancer, and the homeless. All of these students have volunteered their time to help others and we couldn't be prouder of them! Way to go, Townsend Tigers!
#mdpurpose
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sqzu7FSZOgo

Del City Yearbook added 67 new photos to the album: DCHS Soccer Tournament v Ada — at Robert Kalsu Stadium.
February · Del City, OK ·

The soccer teams played three times on Saturday. They played on newly completed field with lots of construction all around. In the early afternoon match the boys defeated Ada 2-0 with scores at the beginning of the game and in the last few seconds. Way to play Eagles!

Carl Albert High School
February 13 at 10:05 PM ·

Congratulations to Taylor Garcia and Hunter Willard for being selected as members of the 2020 Youth Leadership Oklahoma Class. They are two of the 50 total participants selected state-wide.

Fifty of the state’s top juniors from across the state are chosen through a competitive application process and are then taken on a week long educational journey in the summer across Oklahoma, learning lessons about leadership, trust, problem solving, communication, cooperation, career opportunities, but most importantly, why Oklahoma is such a great place to live and work. Way to go!

Del City Yearbook added 92 new photos to the album: Mr and Miss DCHS February 3, 2020 — at First Southern Baptist Church.
February 6 at 5:36 PM · Oklahoma City, OK ·

Logan Bird and Aliyah Dean were crowned Mr and Miss DCHS Tuesday evening. 1st runner ups were Ray Maytubby and Joy Daquioag.
2nd runner ups were Kyle Bratcher and Alliyah Garcia. 3rd runner ups were Josh Bagy and Autumn Dennis. 4th runner ups were Austin Vazquez and Jessica Salmon Additionally, Daybreak and the jazz band provided all the music.
